 succeeded in 0ms:
     1	# Idea 01 — Social Commitment Engine (Individual + Fan DAO)
     2	
     3	## One-line pitch
     4	
     5	A protocol where fans and communities lock conditional vows on-chain before a match — individually or as a collective DAO — auto-executed by TxLINE's Merkle proof when the final whistle blows.
     6	
     7	---
     8	
     9	## Core insight
    10	
    11	The deepest human thing about sport is that it makes people promise things. These promises are everywhere — social media, group chats, locker rooms — and almost none are kept, because there's no enforcement layer.
    12	
    13	TxLINE changes that. The World Cup result is now a trustless, cryptographically verifiable fact on Solana. A smart contract can read the match outcome as truth and execute a consequence automatically. No admin. No committee. No "well technically the rules said..."
    14	
    15	This is not betting. It is a **conditional social contract protocol** where sport is the enforcement mechanism — available to individuals and collectives alike.
    16	
    17	---
    18	
    19	## Two modes, one primitive
    20	
    21	Individual pledges and group DAOs are the **same on-chain primitive at different scale**. An individual commitment is a group of one.
    22	
    23	### Individual mode
    24	
    25	A single fan locks a conditional pledge before a match:
    26	- A fan pledges USDC to a charity if their team wins
    27	- A brand commits to unlocking a product drop if a specific player scores
    28	- A public figure commits to a verifiable on-chain action if an upset happens
    29	
    30	### Group / Fan DAO mode
    31	
    32	A collective governs a shared treasury around a team or match:
    33	- "Brazil DAO" — fans pool funds; if Brazil wins the group stage, the treasury funds a youth football academy in São Paulo
    34	- Any fan can join by depositing before kickoff — **joining is co-signing**
    35	- No formal voting mechanism needed: membership IS the commitment
    36	- When the condition resolves, the entire pooled treasury executes atomically
    37	
    38	Both modes share the same condition language, the same TxLINE proof flow, and the same resolution engine. The only difference is `members.length`.
    39	
    40	---
    41	
    42	## The unified `Commitment` account
    43	
    44	```
    45	Commitment {
    46	  fixture_id:  u64
    47	  strategy:    NDimensionalStrategy   // validateStatV2 payload
    48	  beneficiary: Pubkey                 // charity, cause, wallet
    49	  members:     Vec<Pubkey>            // length 1 = individual, length N = DAO
    50	  vault:       Pubkey                 // escrow PDA holding pooled funds
    51	  status:      Draft | Open | Locked | Resolved | Void
    52	}
    53	```
    54	
    55	| Instruction | Individual | Group |
    56	|---|---|---|
    57	| `create` | Pledger sets condition + beneficiary | Founder sets condition + beneficiary |
    58	| `join` | N/A | Anyone deposits before kickoff |
    59	| `lock` | At kickoff (auto or manual) | At kickoff — no new members after |
    60	| `resolve` | Permissionless after `game_finalised` | Same |
    61	| `claim` / `release` | Funds to beneficiary or refund | Pro-rata refund or full release to beneficiary |
    62	| `void` | Fixture cancelled (`GameState=6`) | Same |
    63	
    64	State machine: `OPEN → LOCKED → RESOLVED_YES | RESOLVED_NO → EXECUTED | REFUNDED`
    65	
    66	---
    67	
    68	## Why this is not betting
    69	
    70	| Betting | Commitment |
    71	|---|---|
    72	| Two parties take opposite financial sides | Only pledger(s) put something at stake |
    73	| Counter-party profits from your loss | Beneficiary is defined upfront |
    74	| Zero-sum outcome | No counter-party on the other side |
    75	| You hedge against your own desire | You want the condition to be true |
    76	
    77	Structurally closer to a conditional donation or a charitable escrow than a sportsbook.
    78	
    79	---
    80	
    81	## The condition language
    82	
    83	Because TxLINE's `validateStatV2` supports multi-stat strategies, conditions can be expressive:
    84	
    85	| Human pledge | Stat strategy |
    86	|---|---|
    87	| "Brazil scores more than 2 goals" | `statKey 1 > 2` |
    88	| "Both teams score AND under 5 total goals" | multi-leg V2: goals each > 0 AND total ≤ 4 |
    89	| "No red cards in the match" | `statKey 5 + statKey 6 = 0` |
    90	| "Clean sheet across both halves" | H1 + H2 period keys (1001/1002) |
    91	| "Home team wins AND corners > 8" | multi-leg V2 across goals + corners |
    92	
    93	A simple UI lets pledgers compose conditions from human-readable templates. The strategy compiles to a `validateStatV2` payload stored on-chain at creation. The condition is immutable once the match starts.
    94	
    95	---
    96	
    97	## The social layer
    98	
    99	All commitments — individual and group — are public. Before the match, anyone can browse what's been pledged: sorted by size, by cause, by condition, by group. During the match, the stakes are visible on the board. After the final whistle, auto-executions land on-chain in real-time.
   100	
   101	A live feed shows: *"$12,000 just released to 14 charities as France scored — including the Brazil DAO (38 members)."* Settlement is a public, verifiable moment that spectators can watch happen.
   102	
   103	---
   104	
   105	## Technical architecture
   106	
   107	```
   108	Individual / Founder composes condition (UI template → validateStatV2 strategy)
   109	  └── creates Commitment PDA (strategy + beneficiary + vault)
   110	        └── [Group] members join via deposit instruction before kickoff
   111	              └── kickoff → commitment locked (no new members / edits)
   112	                    └── match ends → keeper detects game_finalised via SSE
   113	                          └── fetches stat-validation proof from TxLINE
   114	                                └── permissionless resolve tx:
   115	                                      CPI validateStatV2 → true | false
   116	                                        └── true  → release vault to beneficiary
   117	                                            false → pro-rata refund to members
   118	```
   119	
   120	**TxLINE primitives used:**
   121	- `/api/fixtures/snapshot` — fixture universe + cancel detection
   122	- `/api/scores/stream` SSE — `game_finalised` trigger for keeper
   123	- `/api/scores/stat-validation` — Merkle proof package for `validateStatV2`
   124	- `/api/odds/snapshot/{fixtureId}` — display implied probability of condition at creation time
   125	- `validateStatV2` CPI — trustless condition verification on-chain
   126	- `validateFixture` — fixture cancellation / void path
   127	
   128	---
   129	
   130	## Demo flow
   131	
   132	**Act 1 — Individual pledge**
   133	1. Fan opens app, selects an upcoming match
   134	2. Composes condition: "Argentina wins AND both teams score"
   135	3. Sets $50 USDC and beneficiary (charity wallet)
   136	4. Signs — commitment locked on-chain; appears on public board
   137	
   138	**Act 2 — Group / Fan DAO**
   139	5. Founder creates "Argentina DAO" with same condition, beneficiary = youth football fund
   140	6. 12 members join by depositing — pooled treasury builds to $800 USDC
   141	7. Kickoff — DAO locks, no new members accepted
   142	
   143	**Act 3 — Resolution**
   144	8. Match ends — keeper fires `game_finalised` from TxLINE SSE
   145	9. Anyone hits "Resolve" — CPI fires `validateStatV2`
   146	10. Condition met → individual $50 releases + DAO $800 releases simultaneously
   147	11. Live feed updates; Solana explorer links show both settlement txs with Merkle proof
   148	
   149	---
   150	
   151	## Track positioning — DECIDED 2026-07-18: Track 2 primary focus, Track 1 also submitted
   152	
   153	**Two submissions from one build. Focus = Track 2 (Consumer and Fan Experiences)**; Track 1 (Prediction Markets and Settlement, 18k pool) included as secondary with the same engine.
   154	
   155	**Track 1 framing** — the settlement infrastructure is the product:
   156	- On-chain escrow + `validateStatV2` CPI + keeper = oracle tooling
   157	- Group / DAO mode adds collective treasury + permissionless membership
   158	- Every resolution produces a verifiable Solana explorer link
   159	- No admin keys anywhere in the resolution path
   160	
   161	**Track 2 framing (PRIMARY)** — the consumer experience sits on top. Full track brief + judging criteria: [../tracks/track-02-consumer-fan.md](../tracks/track-02-consumer-fan.md).
   162	
   163	What that decision means for the build:
   164	- Lead with the **fan story** — pledge in three taps, watch the board live, see money move when the whistle blows. Cryptography is the trust layer, not the headline.
   165	- **UX polish is judging criterion #1** — frontend gets real time budget.
   166	- **Real-time responsiveness is criterion #2** — the public board and live feed must visibly react to SSE events in the demo.
   167	- **Wallet sign-in required by the track** ("sign up through Solana") — already native to the pledge flow.
   168	- Monetization story for the video: protocol fee on released pledges, brand-sponsored DAOs, white-label for causes.
   169	- The on-chain settlement engine stays — it is the originality criterion vs every other fan app — but framed as "no one has to trust us" rather than as infra.
   170	
   171	**Track 1 submission cost on top of Track 2 build:** second ≤5-min video (infra cut: escrow → proof → CPI → explorer links) + second tech doc. Same repo, same deployment. Budget ~2h at the end; if the clock burns, Track 2 ships alone.
   172	
   173	---
   174	
   175	## Build order (24-hour plan)
   176	
   177	1. Individual `create` + `resolve` + `claim` — core loop, minimal on-chain surface
   178	2. Keeper: SSE listener → `game_finalised` → stat-validation fetch → resolve tx
   179	3. Frontend: create flow, public board, resolve button, explorer link
   180	4. Group: add `join` instruction and members array — additive, same resolve path
   181	5. Demo with seeded historical fixture so video doesn't depend on live match
   182	
   183	**Kill clock:** If group DAO not green by hour 16, ship individual mode only. The individual flow still demonstrates the full TxLINE proof pipeline and is a complete product.
   184	
   185	---
   186	
   187	## What's not in scope
   188	
   189	- Counter-party wagering of any kind
   190	- Anonymous or private commitments
   191	- Formal DAO token voting or quorum mechanics (join = vote)
   192	- Conditions referencing non-TxLINE data
   193	- Mainnet real-money deployment (devnet USDC for hackathon)

